"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514793","Department of Health","false","2016-04-26","<p>The Department has not undertaken or commissioned specific research on the overall impact of immigration on the National Health Service.</p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2016-04-26T07:50:09.937Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514793/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514793/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514793/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-04-21","Health Services: Immigrants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether his Department has undertaken or commissioned research on the effect on NHS services of immigration (a) in general and (b) from nationals of other EEA countries.","false","Biography information for Mr William Wragg","Hazel Grove","William Wragg","35042"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514794","Department of Health","false","2016-04-28","<p>The funding agreed for the community pharmacy contractual framework by the Department and, from 2013-14, by NHS England was:</p><p>2011-12 £2.526 billion</p><p>2012-13 £2.486 billion</p><p>2013-14 £2.8 billion</p><p>2014-15 £2.8 billion</p><p>2015-16 £2.8 billion</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2016-04-28T10:11:33.86Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514794/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514794/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514794/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-04-21","Pharmacy: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how much his Department allocated to the community pharmacy contractual framework in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","35080"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514795","Department of Health","false","2016-04-28","<p>NHS England is responsible for the operational management of the Cancer Drugs Fund and has advised that it is continuing to engage with stakeholders, building on the feedback received during the recent public consultation. A number of engagement activities, including a series of focus groups involving charity and industry stakeholders, will be held during the coming weeks as NHS England continues to shape the operational detail of the new arrangements for the Cancer Drugs Fund.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2016-04-28T13:51:51.497Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514795/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514795/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514795/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-04-21","Cancer: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps his Department is taking to involve stakeholders in developing the operational detail of the new Cancer Drugs Fund.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","35072"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514796","Department of Health","false","2016-04-27","<p>The appropriate interval for follow up appointments will vary between different services or specialties, and between individual patients, depending on the severity of their condition. All follow up appointments (also known as planned, surveillance or recall appointments) should take place when clinically appropriate.</p><p>NHS England’s guidance, “Recording and reporting referral to treatment (RTT) waiting times for consultant-led elective care” is clear that when patients on planned lists are clinically ready for their care to commence and reach the date for their planned appointment, they should either receive that appointment or be transferred to an active waiting list, meaning a waiting time clock will be started and their wait reported in the relevant statistical return.</p><p>Furthermore, the Care Quality Commission (CQC) also assesses providers against the new fundamental standards of safety and quality below which care should never fail. One of the fundamental standards requires that care and treatment must be appropriate and reflect service users’ needs and preferences. Another standard requires that care and treatment must be provided in a safe way. The CQC will require a provider to improve where it is not meeting these standards.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2016-04-27T13:56:38.697Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514796/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514796/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514796/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-04-21","Out-patients: Attendance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what safeguards are in place to ensure that patients who require review hospital appointments are seen within a clinically recommended or safe time.","false","Biography information for Dr Sarah Wollaston","Totnes","Dr Sarah Wollaston","35081"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514797","Department of Health","false","2016-04-28","<p>It is very unlikely that radon would be present in food at levels which would present a risk to consumers. There is, therefore, no requirement to monitor food products for levels of radon (with the exception of bottled water under European Directive 2013/51/Euratom). Radon has a half-life of 3.8 days so if any radon was present at time of manufacture, it is likely to be significantly reduced by the time a product imported into the European Union reaches consumers.</p><p>Food business operators have a responsibility to ensure that food is safe to eat before placing it on the market. The Food Standards Agency is the government department with the responsibility for food safety, including radiological safety. Local food authorities are responsible for appropriate monitoring of radon in bottled water.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","35107","2016-04-28T13:36:27.387Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514797/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514797/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514797/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-04-21","Imports: Radon Gas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps are taken to monitor levels of radon in imported goods.","false","Biography information for Anne Marie Morris","Newton Abbot","Anne Marie Morris","35106"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514798","Department of Health","false","2016-04-28","<p>NHS England is currently undertaking a public consultation on how NHS England's Clinical Priorities Advisory Group (CPAG) will compare competing priorities for National Health Service funding. This consultation closes on 11 May 2016.</p><p> </p><p>Subject to the outcome of the consultation, CPAG plans to meet in June to agree recommendations on the relative prioritisation of new specialised services investments for funding in 2016/17.</p><p> </p><p>In the meantime NHS England continues to have a process in place to consider funding requests for services where there is a high level of clinical critical urgency. It will also consider individual funding requests where there may be a case for funding on the grounds of clinical exceptionality.</p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2016-04-28T13:52:39.043Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514798/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514798/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514798/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-04-21","NHS: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, for what reasons NHS England has not published details of which new specialised services, medicines and interventions it will fund in 2016-17; what assessment his Department has made of the potential effect on patients of such details not yet being provided; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","35069"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514799","Department of Health","false","2016-04-29","<p>Neither the Department nor NHS England has made any such assessment as it would be inappropriate to pre-empt the final recommendations of the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence.</p><p> </p><p>Since 2010, we have spent over £1 billion on the Cancer Drugs Fund (CDF), helping 84,000 patients in England access cancer drugs that would not have otherwise been routinely available to them.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England has advised that the new financial control mechanisms that will apply to the Fund from 1 July 2016 are intended to ensure the fixed £340 million budget is not exceeded, whilst at the same time not limiting the flow of eligible drugs from entering the CDF. Active steps are being taken to ensure that the future arrangements for the Fund are aligned with the final recommendations from the Accelerated Access Review, which are due in the summer.</p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2016-04-29T11:48:32.13Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514799/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514799/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514799/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-04-21","Cancer: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate he has made of the potential (a) number and (b) cost of drugs that might gain conditional approval under the new Cancer Drugs Fund.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","35068"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514800","Department of Health","false","2016-04-28","<p>NHS England has drafted a set of ‘methods documents’ to further refine the process by which new or revised clinical commissioning policies and service specifications are developed for specialised services. This covers the use of both licenced and unlicensed medicines, and has been refined based on clinical and wider stakeholder feedback during 2015/16.</p><p>Since the methods documents need to include the process by which proposals requiring additional investment will be submitted for prioritisation, the methods documents will be finalised and made available to stakeholders following the outcome of the current public consultation on the method to be used by the Clinical Priorities Advisory Group when comparing competing specialised services priorities for National Health Service funding.</p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2016-04-28T13:35:14.537Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514800/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514800/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514800/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-04-21","NHS: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if his Department will publish a (a) timeline, (b) methodology and (c) work programme for the evaluation and development by NHS England of draft commissioning policies for (i) medicines used outside of their licence, (ii) licensed medicines and (iii) service specifications for possible funding from April 2017.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","35073"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514801","Department of Health","false","2016-04-28","<p>It is very unlikely that radon would be present in food at levels which would present a risk to consumers. There is, therefore, no requirement to monitor food products for levels of radon (with the exception of bottled water under European Directive 2013/51/Euratom). Radon has a half-life of 3.8 days so if any radon was present at time of manufacture, it is likely to be significantly reduced by the time a product imported into the European Union reaches consumers.</p><p>Food business operators have a responsibility to ensure that food is safe to eat before placing it on the market. The Food Standards Agency is the government department with the responsibility for food safety, including radiological safety. Local food authorities are responsible for appropriate monitoring of radon in bottled water.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","35106","2016-04-28T13:36:27.45Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514801/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514801/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514801/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-04-21","Food: Radon Gas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, which body is responsible for monitoring levels of radon in food products.","false","Biography information for Anne Marie Morris","Newton Abbot","Anne Marie Morris","35107"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514802","Department of Health","false","2016-04-26","<p>Every death is a tragedy and none more so than that of a child or young person. Any death of a young person with mental health problems in an inpatient service is fully investigated and learned from.</p><p>Although there are systems in place for reporting and reviewing deaths, they are not unified. The Department is urgently looking into this so that an accurate figure can be provided and are in the process of developing more robust arrangements for the future. I will make a written Ministerial statement to the House on this matter following my remarks in the House on 12 April 2016.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2016-04-26T14:05:30.487Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514802/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514802/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514802/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-04-21","Children: Death","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many children have died in (a) NHS and (b) private inpatient mental health units in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","35093"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514803","Department of Health","false","2016-04-26","<p>Any death of a young person in an inpatient service is fully investigated and learned from.</p><p>The systems in place for reporting and reviewing deaths were developed at different times and fulfil different functions. These include:</p><p>- Serious Incident Review for each serious untoward incident;</p><p>- Child Deaths Overview Panels which are carried out at local level into every child death and reported to the Department for Education;</p><p>- Coroners can write to the Secretary of State (or anyone else they feel have lessons to learn) to draw his attention to specific issues of concern after the death of a child; and</p><p>- The Care Quality Commission requires providers to report the death of any detained patient (though few children and young people are detained under the Mental Health Act).</p><p>Prison policy is a matter for the Ministry of Justice.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-04-26T10:24:56.75Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514803/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514803/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514803/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-04-21","Children: Death","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what requirements there are to hold an independent investigation into the unexpected death of a child (a) in a prison, (b) in an NHS-funded inpatient unit and (c) in the community on day release from an NHS-funded inpatient unit.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","35092"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514804","Department of Health","false","2016-04-26","<p>On 22 April 2016, there were 668 children and young people who were receiving inpatient care which had been commissioned by the National Health Service from independent sector providers.</p><p>It is not possible to make a clear distinction between the numbers with a diagnosis of a mental health condition and those who have a learning disability as it will depend on the primary diagnosis linked to the admission and some patients will have a dual diagnosis.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2016-04-26T10:19:05.537Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514804/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514804/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514804/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-04-21","Health Services: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many children who are NHS (a) mental health and (b) learning disability inpatients are in the care of private providers commissioned by the NHS.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","35091"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514805","Department of Health","false","2016-04-26","<p>The University of Bristol has appointed the programme team who will oversee the mortality review programme and has consulted with interested parties on the methodologies and approaches to be used. A pilot review programme is underway in the North East and Cumbria which will be used to inform how the programme operates as it is rolled out. A plan is now in place to roll out the review across all regions of England between now and 2018, with pilots starting in other parts of the country during 2016/17. Additional resources have been made available to support regions in this work.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2016-04-26T10:20:38.713Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514805/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514805/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514805/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-04-21","Learning Disability: Mortality Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what progress has been made on the University of Bristol study of the mortality rates of people with learning disabilities in NHS care, commissioned by NHS England and announced by that body in June 2015.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","35089"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514806","Department of Health","false","2016-04-26","<p>There has been one piece of incoming correspondence from the Southern Health NHS Foundation Trust to the Department on 11 April 2016, which has not yet received a reply.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2016-04-26T10:20:37.323Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514806/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514806/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514806/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-04-21","Southern Health NHS Foundation Trust","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what communication his Department has had with Southern Health NHS Foundation Trust since the warning notice issued to that trust by the Care Quality Commission on 6 April 2016.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","35090"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514807","Home Office","false","2016-04-26","<p>The Home Office does not hold data centrally on the number of police officers who have committed suicide.</p><p>Policing, by its nature, can be a stressful and demanding job and it is the responsibility of chief officers working with directly elected Police and Crime Commissioners and supported by the College of Policing - to ensure that good management systems are in place to ensure the welfare of all officers and staff.</p><p>The Government recognises the importance of police welfare – in October 2014 we allocated £10 million to help support emergency services personnel and volunteers, focused on mental health, physical recuperation and bereavement support for those who need it.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-04-26T11:42:30.89Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514807/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514807/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514807/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-04-21","Police: Suicide","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what estimate she has made of the level of suicide among police officers in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","34987"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514808","Home Office","false","2016-04-27","<p>Our records indicate that the number of applications rejected due to a failure to pay the Immigration Health Surcharge (IHS) from 27 June 2015 to 31 December 2015 is 154. This consisted of 134 rejected for failure to pay the appropriate fee and the IHS, and 20 rejected solely for failure to pay the IHS. There were also an additional 10 cases rejected solely for failure to pay the application fee.</p><p>The payment of the Immigration Health Surcharge was not prescribed for Further Discretionary Leave to Remain application forms until 27 June 2015.</p><p>Notes:</p><p>• The data relates to applications for Further Discretionary Leave to Remain.</p><p>• The data provided is provisional management information that is subject to change. It has not been assured to the standard of Official Statistics.</p><p>• All of the statistics referred to in the answer come with necessary caveats about the accuracy of the data. The data provided has been drawn from manual records on the Home Office Case Information Database, which, as with any large scale recording system, is subject to possible human errors with data entry and processing.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-04-27T10:51:17.637Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514808/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514808/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514808/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-04-21","Immigration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many renewals of existing status of discretionary leave to remain have been refused due to a failure to pay the immigration health surcharge in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Shabana Mahmood","Birmingham, Ladywood","Shabana Mahmood","35013"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514809","Department for International Development","false","2016-05-04","<p>DFID has provided over £18 million in humanitarian and health assistance to conflict-affected people in Kachin and Northern Shan States since 2011, and expects to spend a further £4.9 million this year. We coordinate our assistance with other donors. Other donors have historically supported housing for displaced people. Currently our assessment is that conditions for large-scale return or voluntary resettlement are not present in the absence of a ceasefire and steps towards a peace agreement. We would expect to provide support to return and voluntary resettlement when the political situation permits.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2016-05-04T11:20:07.58Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514809/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514809/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514809/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-04-21","Burma: Internally Displaced People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, whether her Department is providing funding or other support for the resettlement and new housing for internally displaced people in Kachin State, Burma.","false","Biography information for Valerie  Vaz","Walsall South","Valerie Vaz","34994"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514810","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-04-29","<p>Active discussions are underway with key partners and stakeholders to identify where support services for women offenders are most needed across London and what services will be most effective in reducing the number of women entering custody and reoffending.</p><p> </p><p>As a component of our prison reforms, £1.3bn will be invested to modernise the prison estate to make it more efficient, safer and focused on supporting the rehabilitation of offenders. The capital receipt from the sale of Holloway will contribute to this work.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2016-04-29T11:28:33.297Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514810/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514810/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514810/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-04-21","Holloway Prison: Sales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what assessment he has made of the relative merits of investing capital receipts from the sale of HM Prison Holloway in (a) women's support centres in London, (b) improving the women's custodial estate and (c) improving the men's custodial estate.","false","Biography information for Kate Green","Stretford and Urmston","Kate Green","34979"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514812","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-04-26","<p>There is specific legal aid provision for victims of modern slavery and human trafficking for immigration advice and representation, and in relation to damages and employment claims arising from their treatment, subject to means and merits.</p><p> </p><p>The Ministry of Justice and Legal Aid Agency are carrying out a review of existing arrangements for providing legal aid for advice and assistance (known as Legal Help) in respect of Trafficking and Modern Slavery Compensation Claims (TMSCCs).</p><p>The review will involve research into :</p><p>(a) Potential numbers of individuals entitled and eligible to seek Legal Help in relation to TMSCC and their geographical location.</p><p>(b) Ability, preparedness and willingness of legal aid providers to carry out this work, and any factors which may limit this.</p><p>The review will be completed in due course.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara","35052","2016-04-26T16:28:21.243Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514812/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514812/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514812/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-04-21","Slavery","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the (a) terms of reference, (b) timetable, (c) methodology, (d) consultees and (e) identity of the reviewer is for his Department's urgent review of legal aid for victims of modern slavery and trafficking who want to bring claims against their traffickers.","false","Biography information for Sarah Champion","Rotherham","Sarah Champion","35053"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514813","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-04-29","<p>As of March 2016, over 99% of UHT milk products used in prisons are being purchased from UK suppliers. From May 2017, the Ministry of Justice intends to make all contracts Bonfield Scorecard compliant, which includes focusing on the value of local production.</p><p> </p><p>NOMS do not keep a breakdown of expenditure for types of food purchased (i.e. dairy).</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2016-04-29T13:50:03.433Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514813/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514813/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514813/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-04-21","Prisons: Dairy Products","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what proportion of dairy products procured for British prisons was sourced from British producers in the last period for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Nick Smith","Blaenau Gwent","Nick Smith","35034"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514814","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-04-26","<p>There is specific legal aid provision for victims of modern slavery and human trafficking for immigration advice and representation, and in relation to damages and employment claims arising from their treatment, subject to means and merits.</p><p> </p><p>The Ministry of Justice and Legal Aid Agency are carrying out a review of existing arrangements for providing legal aid for advice and assistance (known as Legal Help) in respect of Trafficking and Modern Slavery Compensation Claims (TMSCCs).</p><p>The review will involve research into :</p><p>(a) Potential numbers of individuals entitled and eligible to seek Legal Help in relation to TMSCC and their geographical location.</p><p>(b) Ability, preparedness and willingness of legal aid providers to carry out this work, and any factors which may limit this.</p><p>The review will be completed in due course.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara","35053","2016-04-26T16:28:21.18Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514814/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514814/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514814/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-04-21","Slavery","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether it is the Government's policy to provide legal aid to enable victims of modern slavery and trafficking to bring compensation claims against their traffickers.","false","Biography information for Sarah Champion","Rotherham","Sarah Champion","35052"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514815","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-04-26","<p>The benchmark staffing level has been designed to be safe, decent and secure. Safe, decent and secure operating levels were agreed with the Governor in each prison as the basis for the application and implementation of the prison’s tailored benchmark report. As the benchmark is implemented, there is the facility for Governors to request an evidenced change in their benchmark level.</p><p> </p><p>The evidence that the Harris Review drew on related to a period prior to full implementation of the benchmarked staffing levels. Nationally, we appointed 2,250 new prison officers over the last year and this recruitment drive means we have 440 more full-time prison officers in our prisons than there were twelve months ago.</p><p> </p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2016-04-26T14:55:39.54Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514815/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514815/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514815/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-04-21","Prisons: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, if he will make a reassessment of the evidence used by the Harris Review in forming its recommendation 20, on benchmarking of staffing levels in prisons.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","35108"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514816","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-04-29","<p>Expenditure on food for prisoners for the past three years was:</p><p>2012-13 - £59.6m</p><p>2013-14 - £55.1m</p><p>2014-15 - £54.1m</p><p> </p><p>In the period September 2015 to March 2016, 49% of the total expenditure was spent with British producers.</p><p> </p><p>As of March 2016, over 99% of UHT milk products used in prisons are being purchased from UK suppliers. From May 2017, the Ministry of Justice intends to make all contracts Bonfield Scorecard compliant, which includes focusing on the value of local production.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2016-04-29T13:52:55.13Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514816/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514816/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514816/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-04-21","Prisons: Food","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the annual budget was for food procured for prisons in each of the last three years; and what proportion of such food was sourced from British producers in the most recent period for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Nick Smith","Blaenau Gwent","Nick Smith","35065"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514819","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-28","<p>9 staff work at the Centre for Connected and Autonomous Vehicles. 5 are employed by the Department for Transport and 4 are employed by the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-04-28T08:40:55.3Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514819/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514819/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514819/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-21","Centre for Connected and Autonomous Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many staff work at the Centre for Connected and Autonomous Vehicles; and where those staff are drawn from.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","35078"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514820","Women and Equalities","false","2016-04-26","<p>The Women’s Business Council was established in 2012 to advise the Government on how to support women and maximise their contribution to economic growth. The Ministers for Women and Equalities regularly meet with the Council and its Chair to set strategic direction and support the development of business to business toolkits.</p><p>Most recently, we have supported Council members such as Barclays in launching their ‘Come Back’ toolkit for businesses to encourage and support women to return to the workplace after a career break. We have also worked with the Council member from Deloitte in producing the ‘Trailblazers’ transparency report, to share business best practice on tackling the gender pay gap. We have also engaged with Deloitte in their April 2016 report highlighting best practice to support and encourage female entrepreneurs.</p><p>The Government has taken into account the Women’s Business Council’s reports and recommendations when developing policy options and programmes. In particular their evidence papers and analysis has informed our policies on closing the gender pay gap, increasing the numbers of women into senior positions and encouraging women and girls to take up STEM qualifications. This builds upon work already done by the Government in line with the Council’s recommendations such as the right to request flexible working and shared parental leave and supporting the National Careers Service in launching the ‘Your Daughter’s Future’ toolkit to raise parental awareness regarding career opportunities for girls and women.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","35086","2016-04-26T16:10:55.707Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514820/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514820/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514820/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2016-04-21","Women's Business Council","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, what steps she has taken to support the work of the Women's Business Council.","false","Biography information for Ruth Cadbury","Brentford and Isleworth","Ruth Cadbury","35087"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514821","Women and Equalities","false","2016-04-26","<p>The Women’s Business Council was established in 2012 to advise the Government on how to support women and maximise their contribution to economic growth. The Ministers for Women and Equalities regularly meet with the Council and its Chair to set strategic direction and support the development of business to business toolkits.</p><p>Most recently, we have supported Council members such as Barclays in launching their ‘Come Back’ toolkit for businesses to encourage and support women to return to the workplace after a career break. We have also worked with the Council member from Deloitte in producing the ‘Trailblazers’ transparency report, to share business best practice on tackling the gender pay gap. We have also engaged with Deloitte in their April 2016 report highlighting best practice to support and encourage female entrepreneurs.</p><p>The Government has taken into account the Women’s Business Council’s reports and recommendations when developing policy options and programmes. In particular their evidence papers and analysis has informed our policies on closing the gender pay gap, increasing the numbers of women into senior positions and encouraging women and girls to take up STEM qualifications. This builds upon work already done by the Government in line with the Council’s recommendations such as the right to request flexible working and shared parental leave and supporting the National Careers Service in launching the ‘Your Daughter’s Future’ toolkit to raise parental awareness regarding career opportunities for girls and women.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","35087","2016-04-26T16:10:55.643Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514821/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514821/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514821/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2016-04-21","Women's Business Council","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, whether the Government has incorporated any research recommendations from the Women's Business Council into government policy or legislative proposals.","false","Biography information for Ruth Cadbury","Brentford and Isleworth","Ruth Cadbury","35086"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514822","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-04-26","<p>The Department does not hold information on the proportion of people who have been diagnosed with autism or Asperger's syndrome in each of the last five years who have been in employment</p><p>As is described in the Government’s Autism Strategy, a number of government departments and agencies are working to update or improve a range of data on people with autism, in order to build up a better understanding of their challenges and needs.</p><p>The Government’s Autism Strategy, and the updated Statutory Guidance published in March 2015, sets out in detail how Government will support the autism agenda nationally.</p><p>The Autism Strategy can be viewed here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/think-autism-an-update-to-the-government-adult-autism-strategy" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/think-autism-an-update-to-the-government-adult-autism-strategy</a></p><p>The Statutory Guidance can be found here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/adult-autism-strategy-statutory-guidance" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/adult-autism-strategy-statutory-guidance</a></p><p><strong> </strong></p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-04-26T16:45:53.637Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514822/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514822/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514822/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-04-21","Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what information his Department holds on the proportion of people who have been diagnosed with autism or Asperger's syndrome and who have been in employment in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Melanie Onn","Great Grimsby","Melanie Onn","35088"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514823","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-04-27","<p>This information requested is not held centrally.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2016-04-27T15:55:12.39Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514823/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514823/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514823/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-04-21","Social Security Benefits: Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what proportion of appeals relating to (a) employment and support allowance, (b) disability living allowance and (c) personal independence payment from people claiming for (i) mental health conditions and (ii) other medical conditions have been successful to date.","false","Biography information for Dr Lisa Cameron","East Kilbride, Strathaven and Lesmahagow","Dr Lisa Cameron","35060"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514824","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-04-27","<p>The first in a series of quarterly publications regarding Child Support Agency Case closure are scheduled to be published on the 11<sup>th</sup> May 2016.</p><p>This publication will include the number of segment 2 cases that have been fully closed up to December 2015.</p><p> </p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-04-27T09:15:15.857Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514824/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514824/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514824/answer","Witham","Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514824/answer/previousversion/57676","Biography information for Priti Patel","29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-04-21","Children: Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many Segment 2 non-compliant cases have been fully closed on the CSA 1993/2003 systems.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","35024"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514825","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-04-28","<p>Statistics for the relevant main disabling conditions recorded for Employment and Support Allowance <strong>(ESA)</strong> and Disability Living Allowance <strong>(DLA)</strong> claimants, are given in the tables below:</p><p><strong>Table 1 – Employment and Support Allowance (ESA) recipients with main disabling condition of Pervasive Development Disorders (PDD), Great Britain: August 2015</strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p><strong>ESA</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>All conditions</p></td><td><p>2,355,160</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Pervasive Development Disorders</p></td><td><p>9,920</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Source: DWP 100% data</p><p><strong>Table 2 – Disability Living Allowance (DLA) (cases in payment) by specified main disabling conditions of Asperger’s Syndrome, Autism and Other learning difficulties, Great Britain: August 2015</strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p><strong>DLA</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>All conditions</p></td><td><p>3,020,610</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Asperger's Syndrome</p></td><td><p>38,320</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Autism</p></td><td><p>118,080</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Other Learning Difficulties (inc. Asperger's Syndrome and Autism)</p></td><td><p>142,910</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Source: DWP 100% data</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Such information as is available on Personal Independence Payment <strong>(PIP)</strong> awards for those whose main disabling condition is listed as Autistic Spectrum Disorder is published on Gov.UK: <a href="https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/" target="_blank">https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk</a></p><p> </p><p>Guidance on how to use Stat-Xplore can be found here: <a href="https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/index.html" target="_blank">https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/index.html</a>.</p><p> </p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-04-28T14:08:03.127Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514825/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514825/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514825/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-04-21","Social Security Benefits: Autism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many claimants of (a) employment and support allowance, (b) disability living allowance and (c) personal independence payments have been diagnosed with autistic spectrum disorder.","false","Biography information for Dr Lisa Cameron","East Kilbride, Strathaven and Lesmahagow","Dr Lisa Cameron","34999"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514826","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-04-29","<p>With support from Autism Alliance UK, we are delivering a national training programme to build greater knowledge and understanding and develop a national team of Autism Leads. So far, this course has been delivered to staff members in the North East, North West, Central England, London and the Home Counties and Wales. Staff in Scotland and the South East will be receiving it shortly.</p><p>The Department is also working with Autism Alliance UK to develop an ‘Autism and associated Hidden Impairment Network’ across Jobcentre Plus.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-04-29T13:25:32.853Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514826/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514826/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514826/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-04-21","Jobcentre Plus: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what specialist training is available for advisers in Jobcentres on dealing with applicants with autistic spectrum disorder.","false","Biography information for Dr Lisa Cameron","East Kilbride, Strathaven and Lesmahagow","Dr Lisa Cameron","35000"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514827","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-04-28","<p>Testing of the migration of legacy claimants onto Universal Credit will take place during 2017. Following this national migration will commence in 2018 and by 2020/21 the move to Universal Credit will be complete.</p><p> </p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-04-28T07:34:15.23Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514827/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514827/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514827/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-04-21","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what his Department's timetable is for transferring employment and support allowance claimants to universal credit.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Reynolds","Stalybridge and Hyde","Jonathan Reynolds","34997"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514828","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-04-28","<p>All claimants are required to accept a claimant commitment as a condition of entitlement for receiving universal credit. Claimants who are not subject to work-related requirements will do this through the online claims process.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>However, we have the ability to lift this requirement where it is appropriate to do so, either temporarily or in the longer-term, including for those claimants in the support group of Employment and Support Allowance.</p><p> </p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-04-28T09:40:46.887Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514828/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514828/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514828/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-04-21","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether support group claimants will be required to sign a claimant commitment when they are transferred to universal credit.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Reynolds","Stalybridge and Hyde","Jonathan Reynolds","34995"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514829","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-04-28","<p>We are still developing the processes which will support the managed migration of existing claimants to Universal Credit. Claimants will be contacted in good time to inform them of the steps they will need take to be moved to Universal Credit.</p><p> </p><p>Claimants who are in receipt of the Support Component in ESA at the point they are transferred to Universal Credit will have the Limited Capability for Work and Work-related activity element in UC applied to their UC award from the start of their first assessment period.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-04-28T10:39:34.227Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514829/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514829/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514829/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-04-21","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether claimants in the support group are required to make new claims when they are transferred to universal credit.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Reynolds","Stalybridge and Hyde","Jonathan Reynolds","34996"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514830","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-04-26","<p>If all the necessary information is received with the Funeral Expenses Payments claim form the application is processed straight away. The department is committed to ensuring that communications on eligibility for Funeral Payments are improved. This will in turn help claims to be processed and decisions to be made more quickly.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>For 2016/17 DWP aims to clear Funeral Expenses Payments claims within 15 working days. In 2014/15 of the 51,000 applications, over 55% were cleared within target; and over 69% cleared within 21 working days.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-04-26T14:44:39.82Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514830/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514830/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514830/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-04-21","Funeral Payments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether he has considered measures to expedite the current five to six week processing time for applications to the Department for Work and Pensions Funeral Fund; and what the target processing time is for applications to that Fund.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","35018"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514831","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-04-26","<p>Management Information is held only since 2013 and is provided here:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>2013 - 2014</p></td><td><p>2014 - 2015</p></td><td><p>2015 - 2016</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Bereavement Benefit</p></td><td><p>94.33</p></td><td><p>83.87</p></td><td><p>78.49</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Maternity Allowance</p></td><td><p>70.21</p></td><td><p>66.19</p></td><td><p>72.46</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Industrial Injuries Disablement Benefit</p></td><td><p>191.97</p></td><td><p>165.63</p></td><td><p>149.40</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Social Fund</p></td><td><p>798.46</p></td><td><p>411.34</p></td><td><p>349.78</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Budgeting Loans and Crisis Loans were previously part of the Social Fund and staff that were previously doing this work have been re-assigned to other work.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-04-26T14:57:41.64Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514831/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514831/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514831/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-04-21","Social Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many employees there were in the Social Fund and Specialist Benefits Team on 1 April (a) 2010, (b) 2011, (c) 2012, (d) 2013, (e) 2014, (f) 2015 and (e) 2016.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","35019"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514832","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-04-27","<p>DWP recognise that some people will need help with on-line claims and activity. Those people without digital skills will be offered support in our offices to make and manage their claims on-line, and also to acquire or improve core digital skills.</p><p> </p><p>DWP has also rolled out the Universal Support initiative alongside the national roll out of Universal Credit, as part of which Local Authorities deliver both digital and budgeting support.</p><p> </p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-04-27T09:19:35.837Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514832/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514832/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514832/answer","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514832/answer/previousversion/57699","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-04-21","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate his Department has made of the number of universal credit claimants who do not have basic digital skills; and whether his Department has plans to reduce the number of such claimants without those skills.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","35020"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514833","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-04-26","<p>DWP currently employs 87 people in the Jobcentre Plus office in Tweedale House Oldham (as of 31 March 2016). There are no specific plans to reduce staffing levels in the Oldham Jobcentre Plus office.</p><p> </p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-04-26T09:57:06.78Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514833/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514833/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514833/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-04-21","Jobcentres: Oldham","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether his Department plans to reduce staffing levels in the Jobcentre Plus facility in Oldham in the next five years.","false","Biography information for Jim McMahon","Oldham West and Royton","Jim McMahon","34991"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514834","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-04-29","<p>The information available on the number of Employment and Support Allowance recipients, by duration, phase of claim and whether an IB Reassessment, is published and can be found at:</p><p><a href="http://tabulation-tool.dwp.gov.uk/100pc/tabtool.html" target="_blank">http://tabulation-tool.dwp.gov.uk/100pc/tabtool.html</a></p><p> </p><p>Guidance for users can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/dwp-tabulation-tool-guidance" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/dwp-tabulation-tool-guidance</a></p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-04-29T10:34:05.527Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514834/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514834/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514834/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-04-21","Social Security Benefits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many recipients in the (a) work-related activity group and (b) support group have claimed employment and support allowance or previously, incapacity benefit for (i) up to two, (ii) between two and five and (iii) for five years or more years.","false","Biography information for Steve Rotheram","Liverpool, Walton","Steve Rotheram","34982"
