"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514300","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-05-05","<p>The information requested regarding the number of applications the Criminal Cases Review Commission (CCRC) has received since its creation, is highlighted in the table below. This information can also be located in the published CCRC annual report.</p><p> </p><p>Since its creation in 1997, the Criminal Cases Review Commission (CCRC) has had 20,367 applications. This figure excludes 279 applications that were transferred from the Home Office when the CCRC started operating in 1997. This is broken down as:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Total Applications</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>1997/8</p></td><td><p>1,103</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>1998/9</p></td><td><p>1,037</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>1999/0</p></td><td><p>777</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2000/1</p></td><td><p>800</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2001/2</p></td><td><p>834</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2002/3</p></td><td><p>932</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2003/4</p></td><td><p>885</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2004/5</p></td><td><p>955</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2005/6</p></td><td><p>1011</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2006/7</p></td><td><p>1051</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2007/8</p></td><td><p>984</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2008/9</p></td><td><p>919</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009/10</p></td><td><p>932</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010/11</p></td><td><p>933</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011/12</p></td><td><p>1040</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>1625</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>1470</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>1599</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p>1480</p></td></tr></tbody></table>",,"Lord Faulks",,"2016-05-05T14:07:27.773Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514300/answer","Biography information for Lord Faulks","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514300/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514300/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-04-20","Criminal Cases Review Commission","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many applications the Criminal Cases Review Commission has received in each year since its creation.","false","Biography information for Lord Falconer of Thoroton",,"Lord Falconer of Thoroton","HL7790"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514301","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-05-05","<p>Since its creation in 1997 the Criminal Cases Review Commission (CCRC) had referred 619 cases, to the relevant court, by 31 March 2016. As at 31 March 2016 596 of the referrals had been heard by the court. 406 Appeals have been allowed, 178 have been dismissed and 12 have been abandoned.</p><p> </p><p>This information can also be located in the published CCRC annual report.</p>",,"Lord Faulks",,"2016-05-05T14:21:49.197Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514301/answer","Biography information for Lord Faulks","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514301/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514301/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-04-20","Criminal Cases Review Commission","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many applications the Criminal Cases Review Commission has received since its creation that subsequently succeeded on appeal.","false","Biography information for Lord Falconer of Thoroton",,"Lord Falconer of Thoroton","HL7791"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514302","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-04-27","<p>The Government regularly discusses human rights and reform with the Government of Bahrain. Although there has been a de facto moratorium on the use of the death penalty in Bahrain since 2010, we are concerned that a number of individuals have received death sentences since then. The UK’s opposition to the death penalty is well known. The Parliamentary Under-Secretary for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my Hon. Friend the Member for Bournemouth East (Mr Ellwood), raised the cases of Mr Mohamed Ramadan and Mr Husain Al Moosa with the Bahraini Ambassador to the UK, His Excellency Sheikh Fawaz bin Mohammed Al Khalifa, on 8 March. We continue to monitor these cases closely.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-04-27T15:17:36.67Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514302/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514302/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514302/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-04-20","Bahrain: Administration of Justice","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they will make an urgent appeal to HM the King of Bahrain for clemency in the cases of Mr Mohamed Ramadan and Mr Hussein Ali Musa.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL7792"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514303","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-04-27","<p>We regularly raise with the Government of Turkey issues relating to the management of the border with Syria and the treatment of refugees. We are aware of allegations of civilians being shot trying to cross the border from Syria into Turkey but have seen no evidence to substantiate them. The Office of the UN High Commissioner for Refugees is also unable to confirm these allegations, which have been strongly refuted by the Government of Turkey.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-04-27T15:18:04.127Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514303/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514303/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514303/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-04-20","Turkey: Refugees","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what representations they are making to the government of Turkey about the recently reported killings by Turkish forces of Syrians, including women and children, attempting to flee into Turkey; whether they will call for compensation to be paid to survivors in those families; and what assessment they have made of whether those killings undermine the principles of the EU's agreement with Turkey about refugees and migrants.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL7793"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514304","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-29","<p>The Government intends to publish updated benefit-cost ratios for different phases of the scheme at the next iteration of the relevant business cases, including Phase 1, reflecting all the latest information on costs and benefits.</p><p> </p><p>All published benefit-cost ratios for HS2 account for unexpected costs. For Phase 1, the benefit-cost ratio published in October 2013 in the <em>Economic Case for HS2</em> included contingencies for unforeseen costs. There is therefore no increase to overall costs as a result of the Parliamentary process, as the cost estimate included provision for that process. The benefit-cost ratio was also tested against a range of different cost assumptions.</p><p> </p><p>For the rest of the project, the cost estimates were adjusted for optimism bias. The benefit-cost ratio estimates for the full Y and Phase 2a in latest update, published in November 2015 in the <em>West Midlands to Crewe Economic Case</em>, also accounted for the risk of construction inflation exceeding general inflation over the next five years. This information has been placed in the libraries of the House.</p><p> </p><p>There is no change to the planned opening date for HS2 and HS2 Ltd remain on track to start construction in 2017.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-04-29T11:53:24.873Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514304/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514304/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514304/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-20","High Speed 2 Railway Line","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they will now update the benefit-cost ratios for both Phase 1 of HS2 and the complete project to allow for: (1) extra costs arising from the mitigation and compensation that has already been agreed or should be allowed for as a contingency to cover recommendations of the House of Commons High Speed Rail (London-West Midlands) Select Committee and other Parliamentary committees or official bodies, and negotiations between the Government and affected parties; (2) any extra expenditure required to strengthen the track in order to run trains at the proposed speed, in the light of the research conducted by Professor Peter Woodward; (3) any other costs extra to those allowed for in previous benefit-cost ratio calculations; (4) revised estimates of benefits; and (5) delays in construction and the start of operations not anticipated in previous benefit-cost ratio calculations.","false","Biography information for Baroness Jones of Moulsecoomb",,"Baroness Jones of Moulsecoomb","HL7794"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514305","Home Office","false","2016-04-27","<p>The UK has been operating resettlement schemes for many years and we already have established an effective networks to accommodate and support resettled people. We continue to work closely with Local Authorities to ensure infrastructure and support networks are in place for the appropriate care and integration of these refugees. This includes ensuring suitable housing is available for them. The accommodation provided to refugees resettled in the UK under the Syrian VPR programme is likely to be private rented accommodation and will be within existing local housing allowance rates. We are not looking to host Syrian refugees in people's homes.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-04-27T12:42:11.123Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514305/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514305/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514305/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-04-20","Refugees: Syria","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether it is their intention that the 20,000 refugees being brought to the UK before 2020 will be housed in local authority accommodation or hosted by British families.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL7795"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514306","Home Office","false","2016-04-25","<p>The UK has worked closely with the UN High Commissioner for Refugees on both the development and delivery of its Syrian Vulnerable Persons Resettlement Scheme.</p><p>Through the International Organisation for Migration the UK offers cultural orientation pre-departure to refugees being resettled to the UK. Upon arrival, local authorities are funded to provide refugees with a 12 month support package tailored to their individual needs which includes; accommodation, support in addressing any medical and social care needs, integration assistance and English language tuition.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-04-25T15:22:10.827Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514306/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514306/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514306/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-04-20","Refugees: Syria","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether the process of resettling 20,000 refugees by 2020 fulfils the criteria of the UNHCR Integration Programme outlined in its 2013 report <i>The Integration of Resettled Refugees</i>, including provisions for pre-departure information, initial reception, orientation and documentation, social support, employment support, language training, education, healthcare, housing and income support.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL7796"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514307","Home Office","false","2016-04-27","<p>The accommodation provided to refugees resettled in the UK under the Syrian VPR programme is likely to be private rented accommodation and will be within existing local housing allowance rates.</p><p>The first 12 months of a refugee’s resettlement costs are fully funded by central government using the overseas aid budget. At the Spending Review, the Chancellor announced an estimated £460 million over the spending review period to cover the first 12 months’ costs under the scheme. The costs which can be covered from the aid budget include, for example, any education, housing, medical or social care the refugees might need immediately on arrival.</p><p>At the Spending Review the Government committed £129 million to assist with local authority costs over years 2-5 of the scheme. This will be allocated on a tariff basis over four years, tapering from £5,000 per person in their second year in the UK, to £1,000 per person in year five.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-04-27T12:42:44.16Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514307/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514307/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514307/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-04-20","Refugees: Syria","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is the estimated cost of providing accommodation for the 20,000 refugees to be resettled in the UK before 2020.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL7797"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514308","Home Office","false","2016-04-27","<p>We are determined to ensure that no local authority is asked to take more than the local structures are able to cope with. That is why we work closely with local authorities and other partners, including the Local Government Association, to ensure that capacity can be identified and the impact on those taking new cases can be managed in a fair and controlled way.</p><p>This is a voluntary scheme whereby local authorities sign up to accept refugees on a voluntary basis. We have asked them to think very carefully about whether they have the infrastructure and support networks needed to ensure the appropriate care and integration of these refugees before they make an offer of places to the Resettlement Team.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-04-27T12:43:06.117Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514308/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514308/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514308/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-04-20","Refugees: Syria","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what consultation process took place with local authorities in preparation for their policy of bringing 20,000 refugees to the UK by 2020.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL7798"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514309","HM Treasury","false","2016-05-05","<p>The Government’s position is that the UK will be stronger, safer and better off remaining in a reformed EU.</p><p> </p><p>Recently published Government analysis - ‘HM Treasury analysis: the long-term economic impact of EU membership and the alternatives’ – described the evidence that EU membership has supported foreign direct investment into the UK.</p><p> </p><p>It concludes that foreign direct investment flows into the UK would fall by between 10% and 26% if the UK left the EU, depending on the alternative arrangement.</p>",,"Lord O'Neill of Gatley",,"2016-05-05T12:38:07.757Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514309/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514309/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514309/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-04-20","Foreign Investment in UK","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what plans they have to prevent any fall in the amount of foreign direct investment if the UK were to vote to leave the EU.","false","Biography information for Lord Taylor of Warwick",,"Lord Taylor of Warwick","HL7799"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514310","Department for Education","false","2016-04-27","<p>It is highly disappointing that the NUT conference took this stance towards the Prevent strategy.</p><p>The Prevent duty is entirely consistent with schools’ existing responsibilities and it is irresponsible to suggest that it requires teachers to spy on pupils or close down discussion in the classroom. Good schools will already have been safeguarding children from extremism and promoting fundamental British values long before the Prevent duty came into force. Schools provide a safe space for debate and play a key role in helping young people develop critical thinking skills, which increases their resilience to a range of risks, including extremism. We have published guidance on the Prevent duty and made a wide range of advice and materials available to schools through our Educate Against Hate website.</p><p>My officials have met representatives of the NUT to discuss Prevent and we will continue to provide school teachers and leaders with support to keep children safe and build their character and resilience.</p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2016-04-27T16:09:10.213Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514310/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514310/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514310/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-04-20","Schools: Counter-terrorism","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what response they have made to the NUT motion rejecting the Prevent strategy and suggesting that it causes "suspicion in the classroom".","false","Biography information for Lord Taylor of Warwick",,"Lord Taylor of Warwick","HL7800"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514311","Home Office","false","2016-05-03","<p>The Home Office has introduced a mandatory ‘online flag’ as part of the police recorded crime data collection. This allows police forces to record instances of crimes such as online abuse. The Office for National Statistics has also introduced new fraud and cyber questions to Crime Survey for England and Wales. These new questions mean that we should be able to identify those crimes that had an online component and hence be able to provide estimates of cyber crime. This data will be published in due course. Taken together, this data will support a more robust assessment of whether the police are taking adequate steps to tackle online abuse. The Child Exploitation and Online Protection (CEOP) Command is central to protecting children online and works closely with police forces to identify and safeguard victims and pursue those involved in this criminal activity.</p><p>The Child Abuse Image Database (CAID) became operational in December 2014 and all police forces, and the NCA, are now connected to it. The Internet Watch Foundation shared almost 19,000 digital fingerprints of child sexual abuse material with five major global technology firms to enable their removal and prevent the sharing of thousands of images from their platforms and services.</p><p>This engagement with technology firms is essential, and the UK Council for Child Internet Safety (UKCCIS) brings together industry, law enforcement, academia, charities, parenting groups, and government departments (Home Office, Department for Culture, Media &amp; Sport, and Department for Education), to work in partnership to help to keep children and young people safe online. As part of this work, the UK’s Communications regulator, Ofcom, led a working group including Twitter, Facebook, Google, Ask.FM, MindCandy and Microsoft to develop best practice guidance for emerging social media platforms to encourage responsible practice from industry, and ensure children using their services are able to do so in a safe and protected way. This guidance was published in December 2015.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-05-03T14:33:20.58Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514311/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514311/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514311/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-04-20","Internet: Bullying","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of whether the police and technology firms are taking adequate steps to tackle online abuse.","false","Biography information for Lord Taylor of Warwick",,"Lord Taylor of Warwick","HL7801"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514312","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-04-28","<p>The requirement to charter 'shipping to be taken up from trade' can vary widely depending on the circumstances faced; it is therefore not possible to provide exact manning details until the specific requirements are known.</p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2016-04-28T15:37:16.227Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514312/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514312/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514312/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-04-20","Merchant Shipping","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Earl Howe on 19 April (HL7565), whether, in the event of chartering suitable merchant ships from the commercial market, those ships would be manned by British merchant seamen as was the case in the Falklands conflict in 1982.","false","Biography information for Lord West of Spithead",,"Lord West of Spithead","HL7802"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514313","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-05-05","<p>Work to date suggests that the majority of the requirements of the Fleet Solid Support Ships are likely to be classified as non-warlike, allowing the ships to be procured through open competition, to UK and international bidders. Sensitive elements of the ships are expected to be procured through competitions that will be limited to UK only suppliers.</p><p>It is too early to say where the steel to be used in the construction of these ships will be sourced from.</p><p> </p>",,"Earl Howe","HL7804","2016-05-05T13:45:09.673Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514313/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514313/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514313/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-04-20","Royal Fleet Auxiliary","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether the three planned solid support ships for the Royal Fleet Auxiliary will be built in UK shipyards in order to form part of the regular drumbeat of orders required to maintain the strategic capability of a viable UK shipbuilding industry being identified by Sir John Parker in his national shipbuilding strategy.","false","Biography information for Lord West of Spithead",,"Lord West of Spithead","HL7803"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514314","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-05-05","<p>Work to date suggests that the majority of the requirements of the Fleet Solid Support Ships are likely to be classified as non-warlike, allowing the ships to be procured through open competition, to UK and international bidders. Sensitive elements of the ships are expected to be procured through competitions that will be limited to UK only suppliers.</p><p>It is too early to say where the steel to be used in the construction of these ships will be sourced from.</p><p> </p>",,"Earl Howe","HL7803","2016-05-05T13:45:09.753Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514314/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514314/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514314/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-04-20","Royal Fleet Auxiliary","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether the three planned solid support ships for the Royal Fleet Auxiliary will be built of British steel.","false","Biography information for Lord West of Spithead",,"Lord West of Spithead","HL7804"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514315","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-04-26","<p>I refer the noble Lord to the answer I gave on 15 September 2015 to Question HL1943.</p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2016-04-26T16:23:27.84Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514315/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514315/answer","Hansard_Extract__15_September_2016,_HL_1943[1].docx","HL1943 - QnA extract on T26 Frigates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514315/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-04-20","Type 26 Frigates","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is the planned life of the new T26 frigates.","false","Biography information for Lord West of Spithead",,"Lord West of Spithead","HL7805"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514316","Department of Health","false","2016-05-03","<p>Public Health England took over all the public health campaigns formerly run by the Department of Health on 1 April 2013 including Act FAST.</p><p> </p><p>The funding allocated to the Act FAST marketing campaign is as follows:</p><p> </p><p>Table: Act FAST campaign funding</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Financial Year</p></td><td><p>Media Spend</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>£850,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>£940,000</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="4"><p>Marketing spend is defined for this purpose as advertising spend covering only the media costs (inclusive of agency commission).</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>These figures do not include recruitment/classified advertising costs and ad hoc spend under £10,000. All figures rounded to the nearest £10,000.</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2016-05-03T14:29:44.373Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514316/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514316/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514316/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-04-20","Strokes: Health Education","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what funding was allocated by the Department of Health to the Act FAST campaign in 2014–15 and 2015–16.","false","Biography information for Baroness Wheeler",,"Baroness Wheeler","HL7806"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514317","Department of Health","false","2016-05-03","<p>No such assessment has been made.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2016-05-03T16:18:27.093Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514317/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514317/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514317/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-04-20","Strokes","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the number of lives saved as a result of measures in the National Stroke Strategy.","false","Biography information for Baroness Wheeler",,"Baroness Wheeler","HL7807"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514318","Cabinet Office","false","2016-05-05","<p>As the Minister for the Cabinet Office the Rt Hon Matthew Hancock made clear on 27 April, we are committed to protecting taxpayers' money from being wasted on government lobbying government. We are pausing the implementation of this clause into grant agreements, pending a review of the representations made.</p>",,"Lord Bridges of Headley",,"2016-05-05T13:55:13.827Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514318/answer","Biography information for Lord Bridges of Headley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514318/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514318/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-04-20","Lobbying","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether grants administered by the Arts Council will be exempted from new Cabinet Office guidelines that no government grants may be used to lobby.","false","Biography information for The Earl of Clancarty",,"The Earl of Clancarty","HL7808"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514319","HM Treasury","false","2016-05-05","<p>I refer the noble Lord to my written answers of 1 April (HL7342) and 26 April (HL7583, HL7584, HL7585, and HL7586)</p>",,"Lord O'Neill of Gatley",,"2016-05-05T12:36:04.953Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514319/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514319/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514319/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-04-20","London Stock Exchange: Deutsche Borse","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of whether the proposed cross-margining between LCH Clearnet and Euronext, consequent on the takeover of the London Stock Exchange by Deutsche Bourse, will constitute a mechanism for transmitting financial risk; and whether they plan to take any action to limit the likelihood of any increased systemic risk that might result.","false","Biography information for Lord Myners",,"Lord Myners","HL7809"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514320","Cabinet Office","false","2016-04-27","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p>",,"Lord Bridges of Headley",,"2016-04-27T14:05:27.21Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514320/answer","Biography information for Lord Bridges of Headley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514320/answer","UKSA response to HL7810.pdf","Referral Letter","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514320/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-04-20","Manufacturing Industries","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what was the manufacturing output in the UK in the last 12 months for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Baroness Redfern",,"Baroness Redfern","HL7810"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514321","Department of Health","false","2016-04-26","<p>Information is not collected centrally in the format requested.</p><p> </p><p>Did not attend rates for outpatient appointments in England are collected by NHS England in the Quarterly Activity Return. This data distinguishes between first and follow-up appointments but does not distinguish between types of appointments, so it is not possible to identify how many missed appointments relate to post-surgery.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2016-04-26T16:17:16.523Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514321/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514321/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514321/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-04-20","Out-patients: Attendance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many post-surgery follow-up appointments were missed by patients in the last 12 months for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Baroness Redfern",,"Baroness Redfern","HL7811"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514322","Department of Health","false","2016-04-28","<p>It is the role of NHS Improvement (and NHS Trust Development Agency and Monitor before it) to assess the impact of different expenditure items at National Health Service trusts to ensure that NHS trusts and NHS foundation trusts have arrangements in place to secure financial health. Where individual providers find themselves in financial distress, identifying the root cause of issues is often complex. In some cases the situation may be attributable to the long-term fixed costs of Private Finance Initiative (PFI) schemes, whilst in others the principal causes may lay elsewhere (although it is possible the PFI may exacerbate the issue). However NHS Improvement’s focus is then on supporting that individual provider to fix its financial problems, for example through interim financial support or longer term solutions in that health economy.</p><p> </p><p>Information on the reporting of PFI payments in terms of trust’s total income and expenditure and other statutory reporting requirements is contained within individual trust accounts.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong><br> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2016-04-28T11:38:30.063Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514322/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514322/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514322/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-04-20","Hospitals: Private Finance Initiative","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the impact of private finance initiatives on NHS hospitals' budgets in the last 12 months for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Baroness Redfern",,"Baroness Redfern","HL7812"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514323","The Lord Chairman of Committees","false","2016-04-27","<p>The table below shows the date of the count of the last four Hereditary Peers By-elections for which invoices have been received and the amount paid to Electoral Reform Services in respect of each.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Date of count</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Amount paid to Electoral Reform Services</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>7 July 2015</p></td><td><p>£950</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>16 September 2015</p></td><td><p>£950</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>20 October 2015</p></td><td><p>£950</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>24 November 2015</p></td><td><p>£950</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Amounts are exclusive of VAT. The table does not include a recent by-election in respect of which Electoral Reform Services has provided services but not yet sent an invoice.</p><p>In addition to the services they provide in administering and supervising by-elections, engaging Electoral Reform Services provides assurance that by-elections conform to good electoral practice.</p>",,"Lord Laming",,"2016-04-27T14:05:52.387Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514323/answer","Biography information for Lord Laming","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514323/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514323/answer",,,,,"200",,"Chairman of Committees (HoL)","2016-04-20","Hereditary Peers: By-elections","2","House of Lords","To ask the Chairman of Committees what fees were paid, if any, to Electoral Reform Services for conducting each of the last four Hereditary Peers By-elections.","false","Biography information for Lord Steel of Aikwood",,"Lord Steel of Aikwood","HL7813"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514324","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-05-04","<table><tbody><tr><td colspan="2" rowspan="5"><p> </p></td><td colspan="6" rowspan="5"><p>I refer the noble Lord to the answer given by my hon. Friend the Minister of State for Defence Procurement (Mr Dunne), in the House of Commons on 11 April 2016 to Question 32497.</p></td></tr></tbody></table>",,"Earl Howe",,"2016-05-04T14:24:57.507Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514324/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514324/answer","Hansard Extract 11 April 2016, HOC32497.docx","Type 26 Frigates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514324/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-04-20","Type 26 Frigates","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what progress they have made in the development of the Royal Navy's next generation Type 26 Global Combat Ship.","false","Biography information for Lord Campbell of Pittenweem",,"Lord Campbell of Pittenweem","HL7814"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514325","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-04-27","<p>The Ajax and the Warrior Capability Sustainment Programme (WCSP) are separate programmes and different vehicles, albeit they share the same 40mm cannon. The Ajax programme is progressing, with the first unmanned firings from the vehicle completed this month. The first vehicles will be delivered to training schools in 2017, with an initial operating capability scheduled for 2020 and full operating capability forecast for 2025. WCSP is currently in the demonstration phase, with prototype vehicles and turrets now in build and live firing trials planned for later in the year.</p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2016-04-27T15:46:33.463Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514325/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514325/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514325/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-04-20","Warrior Armoured Vehicle","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what progress they have made in the development of the Ajax-tracked reconnaissance vehicle as part of the Warrior Capability Sustainment Programme.","false","Biography information for Lord Campbell of Pittenweem",,"Lord Campbell of Pittenweem","HL7815"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514329","Attorney General","false","2016-04-25","<p>The relevant figures are as follows:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Rape convictions</p></td><td><p>Sexual Assault convictions</p></td><td><p>Domestic violence convictions</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>3</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>6</p></td><td><p>2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>9</p></td><td><p>5</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Consistent with the answer of 14 April 2016, the above relates to offences that took place in the UK that were prosecuted by the Service Prosecuting Authority and subsequently convicted.</p>","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright",,"2016-04-25T15:00:59.95Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514329/answer","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514329/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514329/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2016-04-20","Domestic Abuse and Sexual Offences: Convictions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, pursuant to the Answer of 14 April 2016 to Question 33351, how many convictions there were for (a) rape, (b) sexual assault and (c) domestic violence as a result of prosecutions by the Service Prosecuting Authority in each year since 2013.","false","Biography information for Karl Turner","Kingston upon Hull East","Karl Turner","34803"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514330","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-04-28","<p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>There are 2439 core full time equivalent civil servants working in BIS, including Sheffield and other locations. The Northern Powerhouse is a key ambition of this Government which requires input from officials across BIS and other Government Departments, across a wide range of policy areas. This supports places across the North to work collaboratively to direct and benefit from the Northern Powerhouse agenda.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-04-28T15:30:49.187Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514330/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514330/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514330/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-04-20","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many staff in the (a) Sheffield office at St Paul's Place and (b) London office at 1 Victoria Street work on the Northern Powerhouse agenda and associated work.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","34858"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514331","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-04-25","<p>The Department has not measured all of the non-cashable savings as it would be disproportionate and impracticable to do so for one element of the much wider BIS 2020 organisational change programme. This programme will deliver a new business model for BIS and reduce operating spending by £350m by 2020.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-04-25T14:28:16.07Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514331/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514331/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514331/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-04-20","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills: Sheffield","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, pursuant to the Answer of 20 April 2016 to Question 33961, how he has measured the non-cashable efficiency savings to be realised through closer working, more collaborative and flexible teams following the closure of his Department's office at St Paul's Place, Sheffield.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","34871"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514332","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-04-26","<p>The Permanent Secretary has recently written to the Chairs of the Public Accounts Committee and the Business, Innovation and Skills Committee. His letter contains details of the potential maximum savings from a closure of the Department’s Sheffield office at St Paul’s Place, and can be seen at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/518244/letter-martin-donnelly-sheffield-office.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/518244/letter-martin-donnelly-sheffield-office.pdf</a>.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","34873","2016-04-26T14:50:09.313Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514332/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514332/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514332/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-04-20","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills: Sheffield","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, pursuant to the Answer of 20 April 2016 to Question 33961, what estimate he has made of cashable savings from reduced overnight accommodation after closure of his Department's office at St Paul's Place, Sheffield.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","34872"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514333","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-04-26","<p>The Permanent Secretary has recently written to the Chairs of the Public Accounts Committee and the Business, Innovation and Skills Committee. His letter contains details of the potential maximum savings from a closure of the Department’s Sheffield office at St Paul’s Place, and can be seen at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/518244/letter-martin-donnelly-sheffield-office.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/518244/letter-martin-donnelly-sheffield-office.pdf</a>.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","34872","2016-04-26T14:50:09.393Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514333/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514333/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514333/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-04-20","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills: Sheffield","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, pursuant to the Answer of 20 April 2016 to Question 33961, what estimate he has made of cashable savings from reduced rents after closure of his Department's office at St Paul's Place, Sheffield.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","34873"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514334","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-04-29","<p>Higher Education (HE) institutions are autonomous on staffing matters including pay.</p><p>The New Joint Negotiating Committee for Higher Education Staff (JNCHES) provides guidance on pay and pay related issues in the HE sector, including on pay equality with a view to reducing the gender pay gap.</p><p>My right hon. Friend the Prime Minister has set out this Government’s ambition to eliminate the gender pay gap in a generation. The Government will be introducing regulations which will require all larger employers, including higher education institutions, to publish gender pay gap data and expect employers to start publishing the required information from April 2017.</p><p>We are aiming to commence the regulations for the private, voluntary and public sectors at the earliest opportunity, when the Parliamentary timetable allows and once all issues have been considered. We will provide a £0.5 million package of support to help business calculate, understand and address their gender pay gaps.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-04-29T10:24:36.98Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514334/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514334/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514334/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-04-20","Higher Education: Equal Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what action he is taking to address the gender pay gap in the higher education sector.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","34738"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514335","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-04-29","<p>Sexual assault is a serious criminal offence and we expect all Higher Education Institutions to have robust policies in place to prevent incidents and support victims.</p><p>The Government asked Universities UK to establish a taskforce to explore what more can be done by the higher education sector to prevent, and respond effectively to, incidents of violence and sexual harassment, hate crimes and other forms of harassment, including in relation to LGBT students.</p><p>The taskforce report is likely to include recommendations on appropriately trained staff and enhanced pastoral support. The taskforce is expected to report its findings in the autumn.</p><p>The Government looks forward to receiving the taskforce’s final report in due course.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","34741","2016-04-29T10:25:27.063Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514335/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514335/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514335/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-04-20","Universities: Sexual Offences","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, if he will take steps to ensure that support staff at universities are given adequate training in supporting students who are victims of sexual assault to ensure that that support is given by such staff and not other students.","false","Biography information for Neil Coyle","Bermondsey and Old Southwark","Neil Coyle","34740"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514336","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-04-29","<p>Sexual assault is a serious criminal offence and we expect all Higher Education Institutions to have robust policies in place to prevent incidents and support victims.</p><p>The Government asked Universities UK to establish a taskforce to explore what more can be done by the higher education sector to prevent, and respond effectively to, incidents of violence and sexual harassment, hate crimes and other forms of harassment, including in relation to LGBT students.</p><p>The taskforce report is likely to include recommendations on appropriately trained staff and enhanced pastoral support. The taskforce is expected to report its findings in the autumn.</p><p>The Government looks forward to receiving the taskforce’s final report in due course.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","34740","2016-04-29T10:25:27.127Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514336/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514336/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514336/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-04-20","Universities: Sexual Offences","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, if he will take steps to increase the available support for LGBT students affected by sexual assault whilst at university.","false","Biography information for Neil Coyle","Bermondsey and Old Southwark","Neil Coyle","34741"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514337","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-04-29","<p>In deciding the proposed location of business centres, the nature and current location of service delivery were taken into account. These functions are currently separate and will remain so under the BIS 2020 programme.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-04-29T10:23:59.76Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514337/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514337/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514337/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-04-20","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills: Reorganisation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how the decision was reached to separate the higher education and further education funding business centres under the BIS 2020 programme.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","34761"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514338","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-04-25","<p>I refer the hon Member to the answer I gave to question <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2016-04-14/33959/" target="_blank">33959</a>.</p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-04-25T16:24:55.347Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514338/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514338/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514338/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-04-20","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills: Sheffield","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, pursuant to the Answer of 20 April 2016 to Question 33961, what estimate he has made of cashable savings from headcount reduction after closure of his Department's office at St Paul's Place, Sheffield.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","34874"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514346","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-04-29","<p>There are currently around 80 members of staff from a number of teams working on steel issues across the Department. Around 75 are based in 1 Victoria Street, London and 3 at St Paul’s Place, Sheffield. It is not possible to calculate precisely how many staff are working on industrial manufacturing sectors, as a significant proportion of the Department’s business supports all sectors of the economy, including manufacturing.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-04-29T13:03:02.427Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514346/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514346/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514346/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-04-20","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many staff based in the (a) Sheffield office at St Paul's Place and (b) London office at 1 Victoria Street work on (i) steel policy and (ii) other industrial manufacturing sectors.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","34893"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514347","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-05-03","<p>I refer the hon Member to the answer I gave to question <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2016-04-14/33960/" target="_blank">33960</a>.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-05-03T16:55:36.62Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514347/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514347/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514347/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-04-20","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills: Sheffield","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, pursuant to the Answer of 20 April 2016 to Question 33961, what estimate he has made of the amount of cashable savings to be realised from reduced travel in the event of the proposal to close his Department's office at St Paul's Place, Sheffield going ahead.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","34900"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514348","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-04-25","<p>Land Registry is currently finalising the Annual Report and Accounts for 2015/16. Once the accounts have been finalised and audited by the National Audit Office, Any payments made will disclosed in their Annual Report and Accounts for 2015/16.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-04-25T17:10:19.857Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514348/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514348/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514348/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-04-20","Land Registry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how much the public purse received from the HM Land Registry trading fund in 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","34916"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514349","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-04-25","<p>Reports from 2015 show that the percentage of customers rating Land Registry as good, very good or excellent was 90% in Q3 and 95% in Q4.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-04-25T16:44:42.207Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514349/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514349/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514349/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-04-20","Land Registry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, pursuant to the Answer of 5 January 2016 to Question 19853, what the customer satisfaction score for HM Land Registry was in Quarters 3 and 4 of 2015.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","34941"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514350","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-04-25","<p>I can confirm that I met with PCS and FDA union representatives on Wednesday 3 February this year.</p><p> </p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-04-25T16:46:46.697Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514350/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514350/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514350/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-04-20","Land Registry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, pursuant to the Answer of 22 December 2015 to Question 20023, whether he has met staff representatives in HM Land Registry.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","34940"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514351","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-04-29","<p>The Northern Powerhouse is a key ambition of this Government and requires input from officials across my Department and other Government Departments across a wide range of policy areas</p><p> </p><p>The Government's plan to build the Northern Powerhouse relies on growing the private sector, so that we have sustainable growth for the long term, rather than the location of civil service jobs. Employment across the North of England as a whole is up by 429,000 since 2010, with 158,000 more businesses created.</p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-04-29T13:29:06.523Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514351/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514351/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514351/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-04-20","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, whether as part of the Northern Powerhouse strategy he plans to relocate civil servants based in London to Greater Manchester.","false","Biography information for Jim McMahon","Oldham West and Royton","Jim McMahon","34957"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514352","Cabinet Office","false","2016-04-26","<p>The Joint Intelligence Organisation (JIO) supports the National Security Council and provides advice on national security and foreign policy to the Prime Minister and other senior ministers. Staff in the JIO are drawn from the Cabinet Office and across Government including the MOD, FCO, and Armed Forces. They are employed on a range of terms and conditions including formal and informal, short and long term secondments. They also regularly call on augmentees and expertise from across Government to work on particular projects or issues. Given this flexible approach to resourcing we do not hold the data requested.</p>","West Dorset","Mr Oliver Letwin","34933","2016-04-26T09:34:25.91Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514352/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Letwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514352/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514352/answer","West Dorset","Mr Oliver Letwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514352/answer/previousversion/57353","Biography information for Sir Oliver Letwin","53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-04-20","Cabinet Office: Syria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many Syria-related desk posts within the Joint Intelligence Organisation's Assessments Staff were (a) vacated and (b) filled during 2015.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","34934"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514353","Cabinet Office","false","2016-04-25","<p>I refer the hon. Member to my letter to her dated 9 March 2016.</p>","Weston-super-Mare","John Penrose",,"2016-04-25T10:34:47.37Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514353/answer","Biography information for John Penrose","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514353/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514353/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-04-20","Members: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, when the Minister for Constitutional Reform plans to respond to the hon. Member for Ashfield's correspondence of 24 February 2016 on voter registration.","false","Biography information for Gloria De Piero","Ashfield","Gloria De Piero","34935"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514354","Cabinet Office","false","2016-04-26","<p>The Joint Intelligence Organisation (JIO) supports the National Security Council and provides advice on national security and foreign policy to the Prime Minister and other senior ministers. Staff in the JIO are drawn from the Cabinet Office and across Government including the MOD, FCO, and Armed Forces. They are employed on a range of terms and conditions including formal and informal, short and long term secondments. They also regularly call on augmentees and expertise from across Government to work on particular projects or issues. Given this flexible approach to resourcing we do not hold the data requested.</p>","West Dorset","Mr Oliver Letwin","34934","2016-04-26T09:34:25.973Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514354/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Letwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514354/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514354/answer","West Dorset","Mr Oliver Letwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514354/answer/previousversion/57352","Biography information for Sir Oliver Letwin","53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-04-20","Cabinet Office: Syria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many desk officers within the Joint Intelligence Organisation's Assessments Staff work on Syria-related issues; and how many such desk officers had specialist knowledge or experience related to Syria prior to their appointment.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","34933"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514355","Cabinet Office","false","2016-04-26","<p>The National Security Secretariat (NSS) supports the National Security Council and provides advice on national security and foreign policy to the Prime Minister and other senior ministers. Staff in the NSS are drawn from the Cabinet Office and across Government including the MOD, FCO, and Armed Forces. They are employed on a range of terms and conditions including formal and informal, short and long term secondments. They also regularly call on augmentees and expertise from across Government to work on particular projects or issues. Since 2010 the organisation has also undergone a number of organisational changes. Given the organisational changes and the flexible approach to resourcing we do not hold the data in the format requested.</p>","West Dorset","Mr Oliver Letwin","34843 ; 34849","2016-04-26T09:33:09.24Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514355/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Letwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514355/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514355/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-04-20","National Security Secretariat","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many National Security Secretariat staff have served continuously in that Secretariat since May 2010.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","34851"
