"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514477","Department of Health","false","2016-04-29","<p>The level of provision of infertility treatment, as for all health services they commission, is decided by local clinical commissioning groups (CCGs) and will take into account the needs of the population overall. The CCG’s decisions are underpinned by clinical insight and knowledge of local healthcare needs. As such, provision of services will vary in response to local needs.</p><p>CCGs have a legal duty to have regard to National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) guidelines. As such, NHS England expects that all those involved in commissioning infertility treatment services to be fully aware of the importance of having regard to the NICE fertility guidelines.</p><p>Following a meeting with Fertility Fairness in December 2015, officials from the Department and NHS England is considering options for addressing variation in the prices that CCGs are currently paying for in vitro fertilisation (IVF) treatment.</p><p>Information about cycles of IVF treatment is not collected centrally.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","34890","2016-04-29T12:39:15.04Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514477/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514477/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514477/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-04-20","In Vitro Fertilisation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, which clinical commissioning groups in England fund (a) no, (b) one, (c) two, (d) three and (e) more than three cycles of IVF treatment.","false","Biography information for Richard Fuller","Bedford","Richard Fuller","34891"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514478","Department of Health","false","2016-04-29","<p>The level of provision of infertility treatment, as for all health services they commission, is decided by local clinical commissioning groups (CCGs) and will take into account the needs of the population overall. The CCG’s decisions are underpinned by clinical insight and knowledge of local healthcare needs. As such, provision of services will vary in response to local needs.</p><p>CCGs have a legal duty to have regard to National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) guidelines. As such, NHS England expects that all those involved in commissioning infertility treatment services to be fully aware of the importance of having regard to the NICE fertility guidelines.</p><p>Following a meeting with Fertility Fairness in December 2015, officials from the Department and NHS England is considering options for addressing variation in the prices that CCGs are currently paying for in vitro fertilisation (IVF) treatment.</p><p>Information about cycles of IVF treatment is not collected centrally.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","34891","2016-04-29T12:39:14.977Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514478/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514478/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514478/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-04-20","In Vitro Fertilisation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps he is taking to reduce the cost of IVF treatment to the NHS in England.","false","Biography information for Richard Fuller","Bedford","Richard Fuller","34890"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514479","Department of Health","false","2016-04-28","<p>The Department does not routinely collect this information. However NHS Employers conducted a survey of employers in January 2016, which asked what percentage of junior doctors worked 1 in 4 weekends or more frequently. The data returned reflected a snapshot (rather than the last six months).</p><p> </p><p>Based on a response from 14 employers in England, 40% worked more frequently than 1 in 4 Saturdays.</p><p> </p><p>Our manifesto commitment, which was translated into the mandate that shaped the contract negotiation, was for the National Health Service to standardise urgent and emergency care, it is not about elective care. It is true that some hospitals do elective work at weekends. That is part of the trust’s local decision-making and it is right for the hospital to make that decision.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer","34825 ; 34903","2016-04-28T10:53:13.853Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514479/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514479/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514479/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-04-20","Junior Doctors: Working Hours","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate his Department has made of the number of junior doctors who work at weekends; and if his Department will provide data on the number of (a) weekends and (b) part weekends worked in each month by junior doctors.","false","Biography information for Norman Lamb","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb","34902"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514480","Department of Health","false","2016-04-28","<p>The Department does not routinely collect this information. However NHS Employers conducted a survey of employers in January 2016, which asked what percentage of junior doctors worked 1 in 4 weekends or more frequently. The data returned reflected a snapshot (rather than the last six months).</p><p> </p><p>Based on a response from 14 employers in England, 40% worked more frequently than 1 in 4 Saturdays.</p><p> </p><p>Our manifesto commitment, which was translated into the mandate that shaped the contract negotiation, was for the National Health Service to standardise urgent and emergency care, it is not about elective care. It is true that some hospitals do elective work at weekends. That is part of the trust’s local decision-making and it is right for the hospital to make that decision.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer","34825 ; 34902","2016-04-28T10:53:13.913Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514480/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514480/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514480/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-04-20","Junior Doctors: Working Hours","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the effect of the new junior doctors' contract on elective weekend care.","false","Biography information for Norman Lamb","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb","34903"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514481","Department of Health","false","2016-04-27","<p>Data on recipients of personal health budgets is collected from clinical commissioning groups on a voluntary basis. Numbers are not currently collected for specific conditions so an estimate cannot be made on the number of people with autism who are in receipt of a personal health budget. NHS England is exploring options for formal data collection on personal health budgets and consideration is being given to the cohorts of recipients that will be included in this data collection.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2016-04-27T09:18:05.06Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514481/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514481/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514481/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-04-20","Autism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate he has made of the number of people with autism who are in receipt of a personal health budget.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","34901"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514482","Cabinet Office","false","2016-04-25","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson","34908","2016-04-25T15:17:29.973Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514482/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514482/answer","UKSA Response to 34908 and 34924.pdf","UKSA Letter to Member - Sudden Deaths","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514482/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-04-20","Sudden Adult Death Syndrome","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what information his Department holds on the number of people who died of Sudden Adult Death Syndrome in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","34924"
