"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513956","Cabinet Office","false","2016-05-04","<p>As I made clear in the House on 27 April, we are continuing to consider the comments of all interested parties, ahead of the introduction into grant agreements of the clause aimed at protecting taxpayers' money from being wasted on government lobbying government. We are pausing the implementation, pending a review of the representations made, and to give further time to consider any necessary adjustments to the wording of the clause, or the policy on its implementation, to help to deliver this policy in the best possible way for all involved.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","34672","2016-05-04T09:44:56.497Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513956/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513956/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513956/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-04-19","Lobbying","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, if he will make it his policy to exempt universities and university research from the proposed ban on non-government organisations using funds from Government to lobby Government.","false","Biography information for Mr Andrew Smith","Oxford East","Mr Andrew Smith","34674"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513957","HM Treasury","false","2016-04-25","<p>From April 2017, HMRC will be making publicly available details of alcohol wholesalers who are approved. From then, retailers who buy from unapproved wholesalers will be liable to a fine.</p><p> </p><p>HMRC is now assessing the applications it has received against the scheme’s approval criteria. The number of applications received are lower than HMRCs initial estimate of 21,000 businesses that could be wholesaling alcohol. There could be a number of reasons for this, and HMRC is currently comparing the applications received with original expectations and encouraging businesses that have not applied to do so, to mitigate penalties and the likelihood of enforcement action.</p><p> </p><p>Where businesses have been purposefully fraudulently trading, HMRC will take action. It is too early to report outcomes of any investigations into illicit trading that HMRC are undertaking since the introduction of the scheme.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","34685 ; 34721","2016-04-25T16:26:49.167Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513957/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513957/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513957/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-04-19","Wholesale Trade: Alcoholic Drinks","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the businesses and sectors which have failed to sign up to the Alcohol Wholesaler Registration Scheme; what steps his Department is taking to ensure that such businesses sign up to that scheme; and what steps his Department is taking to exclude from the market those businesses suspected to be trading fraudulently and which did not register by the 31 March 2016 deadline.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","34684"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513958","HM Treasury","false","2016-04-25","<p>From April 2017, HMRC will be making publicly available details of alcohol wholesalers who are approved. From then, retailers who buy from unapproved wholesalers will be liable to a fine.</p><p> </p><p>HMRC is now assessing the applications it has received against the scheme’s approval criteria. The number of applications received are lower than HMRCs initial estimate of 21,000 businesses that could be wholesaling alcohol. There could be a number of reasons for this, and HMRC is currently comparing the applications received with original expectations and encouraging businesses that have not applied to do so, to mitigate penalties and the likelihood of enforcement action.</p><p> </p><p>Where businesses have been purposefully fraudulently trading, HMRC will take action. It is too early to report outcomes of any investigations into illicit trading that HMRC are undertaking since the introduction of the scheme.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","34684 ; 34721","2016-04-25T16:26:49.237Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513958/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513958/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513958/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-04-19","Wholesale Trade: Alcoholic Drinks","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many wholesalers have been found as a result of their failure to sign up to the Alcohol Wholesaler Registration Scheme to have been trading in alcohol fraudulently since the introduction of that scheme","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","34685"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513959","HM Treasury","false","2016-04-25","<p>From April 2017, HMRC will be making publicly available details of alcohol wholesalers who are approved. From then, retailers who buy from unapproved wholesalers will be liable to a fine.</p><p> </p><p>HMRC is now assessing the applications it has received against the scheme’s approval criteria. The number of applications received are lower than HMRCs initial estimate of 21,000 businesses that could be wholesaling alcohol. There could be a number of reasons for this, and HMRC is currently comparing the applications received with original expectations and encouraging businesses that have not applied to do so, to mitigate penalties and the likelihood of enforcement action.</p><p> </p><p>Where businesses have been purposefully fraudulently trading, HMRC will take action. It is too early to report outcomes of any investigations into illicit trading that HMRC are undertaking since the introduction of the scheme.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","34684 ; 34685","2016-04-25T16:26:49.3Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513959/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513959/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513959/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-04-19","Wholesale Trade: Alcoholic Drinks","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many businesses had signed up for the Alcohol Wholesaler Registration Scheme by the 31 March 2016 application deadline; whether the number of businesses was in line with the 20,000 businesses that HM Revenue and Customs estimated could be required to register; and what steps are being taken to tackle any shortfall in numbers.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","34721"
